#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:126
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multi-task"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:129
msgid ""
"Linux belongs to the family of time-sharing operating systems. It divides "
"processing time between several programs, switching from one to another in a "
"transparent way for the user. This implies:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:134
msgid "Simultaneous execution of several programs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:134
msgid "Distribution of CPU time by the scheduler."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:134
msgid "Reduction of problems caused by a failed application."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:134
msgid "Reduced performance in the event of too many programs running."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:135
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multi-user"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:138
msgid ""
"The purpose of MULTICS was to allow several users to work from several "
"terminals (screen and keyboard) from a single computer (very expensive at "
"the time). Linux, inspired by this operating system, kept this ability to "
"work with several users simultaneously and independently, each one having "
"their own user account with memory space and access rights to files and "
"software."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multi-processor"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:142
msgid ""
"Linux is able to work with multi-processor computers or with multi-core "
"processors."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:143
#, no-wrap
msgid "Multi-platform"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:146
msgid ""
"Linux is written in a high-level language that can be adapted to different "
"types of platforms during compilation. This allows it to run on:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
