#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:154
#, no-wrap
msgid "Open"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:157
msgid ""
"Linux is based on recognized standards such as [POSIX](http://en.wikipedia."
"org/wiki/POSIX), [TCP/IP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Internet_protocol_suite), [NFS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Network_File_System), and [Samba](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/"
"Samba_(software)), which allow it to share data and services with other "
"application systems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:158
#, no-wrap
msgid "The UNIX/Linux Philosophy"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:166
msgid "Treat everything as a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:166
msgid "Value portability."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:166
msgid "Do one thing and do it well."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:166
msgid "KISS: Keep It Simple Stupid."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:166
msgid ""
"\"UNIX is basically a simple operating system, but you have to be a genius "
"to understand the simplicity.\" (__Dennis Ritchie__)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:166
msgid ""
"\"Unix is user-friendly. It just isn't promiscuous about which users it's "
"friendly with.\" (__Steven King__)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:167
#, no-wrap
msgid "The GNU/Linux distributions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:170
msgid ""
"A Linux distribution is a **consistent set of software** assembled around "
"the Linux kernel, ready to be installed along with the necessary components "
"to manage itself (installation, removal, configuration). There are "
"**associative** or **community** distributions (Debian, Rocky) and "
"**commercial** distributions (Red Hat, Ubuntu)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:172
msgid ""
"Each distribution offers one or more **desktop environments**, and provides "
"a set of pre-installed software and a library of additional software. "
"Configuration options (kernel or services options for example) are specific "
"to each distribution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:174
msgid ""
"This principle allows distributions to be geared to **beginners** (Ubuntu, "
"Linux Mint...) or fully customizable for **advanced users** (Gentoo, Arch); "
"distributions can also be more adept with **servers** (Debian, Red Hat) or "
"**workstations** (Fedora)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:175
#, no-wrap
msgid "Desktop environments"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:178
msgid ""
"There are many graphic environments such as **GNOME**, **KDE**, **LXDE**, "
"**XFCE**, etc. There is something for everyone, and their **ergonomics** "
"hold their own against Microsoft or Apple systems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:180
msgid ""
"So why is there so little enthusiasm for Linux, when this system is "
"practically **virus free**? Could it be because so many editors (Adobe) and "
"manufacturers (Nvidia) do not play the free game and do not provide a "
"version of their software or __drivers__ for GNU/Linux? Perhaps it's fear of "
"change, or the difficulty of finding where to buy a Linux computer, or too "
"few games distributed under Linux. That last excuse at least shouldn't be "
"true for long, with the advent of the game engine Steam for Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:182
msgid "![GNOME Desktop](images/01-presentation-gnome.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:184
msgid ""
"The **GNOME 3** desktop environment no longer uses the concept of desktop "
"but that of GNOME Shell (not to be confused with the command line shell). It "
"serves as a desktop, a dashboard, a notification area and a window selector. "
"The GNOME desktop environment is based on the **GTK+** component library."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:186
msgid "![KDE Desktop](images/01-presentation-kde.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:188
msgid ""
"The **KDE** desktop environment is based on the **Qt** component library. It "
"is traditionally recommended for users familiar with a Windows environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:190
msgid "![Tux - The Linux mascot](images/tux.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:191
#, no-wrap
msgid "Free / Open Source"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:194
msgid ""
"A user of a Microsoft or Mac operating system must purchase a license to use "
"the operating system. This license has a cost, although it is usually "
"transparent (the price of the license is included in the price of the "
"computer)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:196
msgid ""
"In the **GNU/Linux** world, the Free Software movement provides mostly free "
"distributions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:198
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Free** does not mean free!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:200
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Open Source**: the source code is available, so it is possible to consult and modify it under certain conditions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:202
msgid ""
"A free software is necessarily open-source, but the opposite is not true "
"since open-source software is distinct from the freedom offered by the GPL "
"license."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:203
#, no-wrap
msgid "GNU GPL (GNU General Public License)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:206
msgid ""
"The **GPL** guarantees the author of a software its intellectual property, "
"but allows modification, redistribution or resale of software by third "
"parties, provided that the source code is included with the software. The "
"GPL is the license that came out of the **GNU** (GNU is Not UNIX) project, "
"which was instrumental in creating Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:208
msgid "It implies:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:213
msgid "The freedom to run the program, for any purpose."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:213
msgid "The freedom to study how the program works and adapt it to your needs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:213
msgid "The freedom to redistribute copies."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:213
msgid ""
"The freedom to improve the program, and publish those improvements for the "
"benefit of the whole community."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/01-presentation.md:215
msgid ""
"On the other hand, even products licensed under the GPL can have a cost. "
"This is not for the product itself, but the **guarantee that a team of "
"developers will continue to work on it to make it evolve and troubleshoot "
"errors, or even provide support to users**."
msgstr ""

